ce:section.ce:para:
As mentioned above, N-doping is widespread used for heteroatom doping of GQDs, and N is one of the mostly used elements for co-doping of GQDs. Therefore, our motivation in this work arose from previous work of N-GQDs [30], which include graphitic N, pyridinic N and pyrrolic N configurations [27,31]. The co-doped GQDs in this work mainly consider three elements: B, P, and S, which can be described as N/B co-doped GQDs, N/P co-doped GQDs, and N/S co-doped GQDs, respectively. During synthesis processes, some B, P and S atoms tend to be oxidized to form C − XO − C (X: B, P or S) as observed by x-ray photoelectronic spectroscopy [32,33]. Although PO and SO groups in chemical co-doping are still little known, it is imminently to comprehend the relations between these configurations and fundamental properties of GQDs. Hence, the three co-doped patterns, N/B, N/S, and N/P, are chosen to study, which include BO, PO and SO co-doping with graphitic N, pyrrolic N, and pyridinic N (Fig. 1
                     ). For convenience, graphitic N, pyrrolic N, and pyridinic N are respectively expressed as Ng, Np, and Nh, due to the bonding configurations of pyrrolic and pyridinic N atoms in a pentatomic and hexatomic ring. The OB, OP and OS bonding to two C atoms are described as BC2O, PC2O, and SC2O, respectively. In previous study, it was found that the introduction of heteroatoms into the basal plane of graphene could generate defects and thus change geometry structures, while graphene plane remained with the heteroatoms doped at the edge [11,34]. In this work, we focus on investigating effects of different heteroatoms (B, P, and S) on optical and electronic properties of N-doped GQDs. Hence, in order to reduce the influence of defects in carbon matrix or rearrangement of geometry structures, heteroatoms are doped at the edge positions of GQDs. Meanwhile, to keep the structure with a stable close shell, each of heteroatom doping structure has two symmetric doping sites. In the beginning, we studied the doping of B into graphitic N doped GQDs to evaluate the stability of N/B co-doped GQDs with three doping positions including para-position, ortho-position, and meta-position. As can be seen in Table S1 of Supporting Information (SI), energy varies insignificantly with different doping positions, and the N/B co-doped GQD has relatively low energy with BO doping at the meta-position. Hence, in order to investigate effects of heteroatoms (B, S, P) on electronic and optical properties, the positions are consistent among the three types of heteroatoms introduced into three N doping patterns, as shown in Fig. 1. Pristine GQD (consisting of 54 carbon atoms, C54H18) and GQDs doped with N, N/S, N/P, and N/B are investigated. For simplicity, GQDs doped with N are denoted as GQD–R, GQDs doped with X = O are denoted as GQD–XC2O, and co-doped GQDs are denoted as GQD–RXC2O, respectively, where R indicates Ng, Np, and Nh, X indicates B, P and S. The chemical formulas of GQDs doped with different N patterns are listed in Table 1
                     . Due to O and S containing groups on the surface of GQDs, the GQD has exhibited excellent water solubility [7,35–37], thus all calculations in this work were conducted in water. The solvent was included based on the polarizable continuum model [38]. The ground-state geometries of GQDs and their analogues were fully optimized in water without any symmetry constraints at the B3LYP level of theory with 6-31G* basis sets [39]. The optimizations were all performed with the Gaussian default pruned (75, 302) grid, and the convergence criterion was the default convergence criterion, 3 × 10−4 a. u. for the root mean square of force. The B3LYP hybrid functional has been considered as one of the most accurate functionals to deal with electronic excitations [39–41]. In the preparation stage of this study, we performed TD-DFT calculations with B3LYP and CAM-B3LYP to assess the dependence of absorption spectra on the functionals. The calculated absorption spectra with two functionals are exhibited in Table S2. In addition, the adsorption spectra of pristine C24, C32, C42, and C132 GQDs (containing 24, 32, 42, and 132 conjugated carbon atoms, respectively) with different sizes and shapes were calculated using B3LYP and CAM-B3LYP. The maximum absorption wavelengths calculated by B3LYP are in good agreement with available experimental data, which indicates the methods we chosen are appropriate to explain the absorption process of GQDs. Hence, TD-DFT calculations with B3LYP calculation was performed on the geometries optimized in water to evaluate wavelengths and oscillator strengths in absorption process. The 25 lowest transitions were calculated to simulate UV–vis absorption spectra. The DFT and TD-DFT calculations were performed using the Gaussian09 software package [42]. The configurations to each electronic density and orbital densities were visualized using Multiwfn [43] program.
